<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-89 2343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Walesa 2ndLd-Writethru a0763 11-19 1181</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0763,1208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Puts Business Aside, Urges Americans To Remember Poles' Struggle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with visit ending in New Jersey.
Picks up 9th graf pvs, ```Let us...' ADDS 2 grafs at end to UPDATE with
dinner at Basia Johnson's.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotoPX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lech Walesa drew cheers in this cradle of
American liberty on Sunday when he held aloft the city's Freedom
Award, which martial law had prevented him from getting in 1981,
and declared, ``We are free now.''
   In the morning, the Solidarity leader paused from his goodwill
tour of the United States to pray at the National Shrine of our
Lady of Czestochowa in suburban Doylestown, where he was joined by
an estimated crowd of 10,000 who shouted ``Welcome!'' in Polish.
   During the Mass said in Polish by Cardinal John Krol, retired
Archbishop of Philadelphia, Walesa was hailed as ``a great son of
Poland ... a man of unshakable faith and enduring courage.''
   Walesa spent the afternoon urging union members to support their
counterparts throughout the world. He also picked up the Freedom
Award and another honor, touched the Liberty Bell and ended his
Philadelphia visit with a private reception in Independence Hall.
   Walesa's stop in Philadelphia was the next to the last in this
country. He arrived in Washington a week ago and, after a stop in
New Jersey, was headed for Venezuela on Monday.
   Walesa flew in from Chicago on Saturday night. Chicago, said to
have the largest number of people of Polish descent of any city
except Warsaw, gave Walesa a rousing welcome including a rally that
attracted 20,000 people despite freezing temperatures.
   During his U.S. visit, he has also met with the president,
addressed a joint session of Congress and had numerous meetings
with business and industry leaders in his quest to find more
investors in the troubled Polish economy.
   The Nobel Peace Prize laureate ended his whirlwind tour Sunday
night with a visit to St. Hedwig's Roman Catholic Church in
Trenton, N.J., where he laid a wreath at a shrine for Father Jerzy
Popieluszko, the Polish activist priest who was murdered five years
ago.
   As Walesa entered the church, he was greeted by loud applause
and the singing of the Polish national anthem by about 1,500
Polish-Americans. Many of those gathered stood on pews and had
tears in their eyes.
   ``I am an example of the small person who can do great things,''
Walesa told the assembly. ``I am proof of the adage that faith can
move mountains. I believe in freedom and liberty and in democracy
and I didn't have an army.''
   Earlier Sunday in Philadelphia, Walesa said that he was putting
business aside for the day and instead urged listeners to ponder
the chain of events that brought a measure of democracy to his
country over the past year.
   ``Let us remember the road behind us,'' he said through an
interpreter at a ceremony after a breakfast in suburban Fort
Washington. ``Maybe we have to think over what we have done. Maybe
we have to remember.''
   He then rang a lifesize replica of the Liberty Bell, a symbol of
American freedom, three times to emphasize his words.
   The breakfast was sponsored by the Copernicus Society, a
Polish-American philanthropic group. One of the guests, Former U.S.
Supreme Court Chief Justice Warren Burger, counseled Walesa on how
to build checks and balances into a new government.
   Burger told Walesa that he hoped Poles ``look to our experience
... that we divided the power'' among three equal branches of
government _ judicial, executive and legislative. ``That has been
what has preserved human liberty,'' he said.
   Also attending the gathering was author James Michener, who
lives in nearby New Hope. ``I cannot tell you how excited someone
like me is ... to see the collapse of a false idea that could rule
the people but not feed them,'' Michener said. ``That is a
revolution of a magnitude that staggers me.''
   A few miles away in Doylestown, the morning temperatures were in
the 20s. But thousands gathered on the sloping, sunlit meadow in
front of the shrine and cathedral hours before Walesa showed up for
the Mass.
   Walesa spoke after the service, starting from a prepared text
and then dropping his notes to ``speak from the heart.''
   ``We are building a proud Poland. We are building a faithful
Poland. We are building a Poland for all Poles,'' he said as the
crowd reacted with cheers to his unprepared remarks. Next to him
was folk singer Joan Baez, who sang a 1980 Solidarity strike song.
   After the Mass, Walesa traveled downtown to meet with about 100
area union leaders at the headquarters of the International Ladies
Garment Workers Union in Philadelphia. Walesa asked the audience to
join with him to protect the rights of working people everywhere.
   ``People in many regions of the world are in need of our common
support. Some people are even now jumping over the fence as I did
10 years ago,'' said Walesa, who first came to prominence when he
jumped over a fence to join striking Lenin shipyard workers in
Gdansk, Poland.
   From the union hall, he walked to the home of American
Revolution hero Thaddeus Kosciuszko, where he received the Freedom
Award, and then paraded with a string band to the Polish-American
Cultural Center.
   As he walked to the entry of the historic home, Walesa dove into
the crowd, shaking hands. To cheering and whistling, Walesa held
the medal aloft and spoke of his homeland in 1981, when he was
awarded the honor but unable to collect it because of martial law.
   ``It's clear that (eight years ago) I couldn't have carried this
medal of freedom to a country that isn't free,'' he said. ``We are
free now.''
   At the Liberty Bell, Walesa received a copy of the city's
Liberty Medal, a $100,000 award established this year to recognizes
leadership in the pursuit of liberty. The presentation was a
formality because Walesa's wife, Danuta, had accepted the medal
during a ceremony July 4th.
   As Hobart Cawood, director of the Independence National Historic
Park, explained how the bell rang to signal the Declaration of
Independence more than 200 years ago, Walesa studied the bell's
crack.
   ``Perhaps modern technology could stop this crack?'' he asked,
smiling. The crowd of invited dignitaries laughed.
   As hundreds of people outside chanted ``We want Lech!'' Walesa
turned and flashed two fingers in a ``V'' saying, ``This should be
the medal of Freedom and Liberty and Victory as well.''
   In New Jersey Sunday night, Walesa was a dinner guest at the
Princeton estate of Barbara Piasecka Johnson, the 52-year-old
Polish-born woman who inherited much of the Johnson &amp; Johnson
pharmaceutical fortune.
   Mrs. Johnson in June announced that she would spend up to $100
million for a 55 percent interest in the Lenin shipyard in Gdansk,
where the Solidarity movement was first kindled by Walesa in 1980.
The shipyard was scheduled to be shut down by Poland's Communist
government, who said it was unprofitable.
</TEXT>
