<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Communists     11-19 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Communists,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Communists Hold Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's tiny, hard-line Communist Party welcomed
the dramatic changes in Eastern Europe as delegates gathered
Saturday for the annual party congress.
   There are two communist parties here _ the hard-line Communist
Party of Britain and the Communist Party of Great Britain. The
Communist Party of Britain broke with the original party in 1987,
accusing it of revisionism.
   In 1987 the Communist Party of Great Britain gave up talk of
class war and declared it would follow a ``realist'' approach. It
claims 7,500 members.
   The Communist Party of Britain, which began its two-day session
congress Saturday, reports a membership of about 1,800.
   Delegates on Saturday praised Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's efforts to restructure the economy and East Germany's
Communist Party leadership for opening the Berlin Wall.
   Party chairman Derek Robinson told the 120 delegates, ``We are
living in a most exciting period of socialist developments in the
world.'' He said communism will provide the inspiration for further
changes in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   Robinson said that Britain, under 10 years of government by
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservatives, has seen rising
unemployment, an erosion of democracy and systematic attacks on the
union movement.
   Delegates arriving for the congress were greeted by a small
group of demonstrators whose spokesman said they believed in a
``reforged Communist Party,'' and neither the Communist Party of
Britain or the Communist Party of Great Britain was true to
communist ideals.
</TEXT>
