<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0651 11-19 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0651,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with Terris obit, which moved as a separate as a0667.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Zola Ross</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zola Helen Ross, the author of dozens of novels
and children's books, died Tuesday at age 82.
   Ross, whose books included the Western historical novels
``Spokane Saga,'' ``The Green Land,'' ``Overdue for Death,'' ``The
Golden Witch,'' ``Cassy Scandal,'' ``Reno Crescent and ``Bonanza
Queen,'' died in a convalescent home after an extended illness.
   Ross was also a writing teacher and cofounder of the Pacific
Northwest Writers Conference.
   Her students published more than 400 books. In 1974 about 30
successful writers threw a ``gratitude party'' in which they
claimed she was responsible for ``more publishing authors than any
other writing teacher in the United States.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Norma Terris</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norma Terris, who rocketed to stardom in the
original production of the musical ``Show Boat,'' died Wednesday
after a brief illness. She was 87.
   Miss Terris died at her summer home in Lyme, Conn. She also had
a home in Palm Beach, Fla.
   The Columbus, Kan., native won critical acclaim for her
performance as Magnolia in the Florenz Ziegfeld production of
``Show Boat,'' which was written by Jerome Kern and Oscar
Hammerstein II. It opened on Broadway in 1927 and ran for 2{ years.
   Kern and Hammerstein wrote ``Why Do I Love You?'' _ one of the
show's enduring songs _ for Miss Terris during rehearsals.
   In 1932, she repeated her success in a Broadway revival of
``Show Boat.''
   Miss Terris appeared in Hollywood movies in the 1930s. During
the '30s and '40s she was a star of St. Louis' Municipal Opera
Company.
</TEXT>
