<FIRST>r w AM-Salvador-Protest 1stLd-Writethru a0662 11-19 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts 1 graf after 3rd pvs with Chicago protest.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ninety-six Arrested Protesting U.S. Aid to El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia police arrested 96 people
in front of the White House Saturday during a demonstration against
U.S. aid to the government of El Salvador, authorities said.
   Ninety-five of the demonstrators were carried away by police
when they sat in the middle of Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the
White House, said police spokesman Sgt. Joseph Gentile. He said
they were charged with blocking a public space while one protester
was charged with assaulting a police officer.
   About 1,000 demonstrators took part in the rally, which was
sponsored by the Committee in Solidarity with the People of El
Salvador.
   A rally in Chicago resulted in the arrests of 36 people in front
of the Consulate of El Salvador, said police spokeswoman Patricia
Mooney. An estimated 20,000 people were attending a rally for
visiting Polish labor leader Lech Walesa when the arrests occurred.
The group was charged with mob action and resisting after police
carried the protesters to squad cars, Ms. Mooney said.
   The protesters marched from the State Department to the
Organization of American States and the White House. Most stood on
the street curb chanting ``The whole world is watching, the whole
world is watching,'' as some refused police orders to leave the
street and were hauled away in chartered buses.
   According to Gentile, the 95 who were charged with blocking the
street _ formally called ``incommoding'' _ were given the option of
paying a $50 fine or facing trial. Conviction at trial carried a
maximum penalty of 90 days in jail and the fine.
   The name of the person arrested on the assault charge was not
released and it could not be determined late Saturday if the person
was kept in jail.
</TEXT>
