<FIRST>u a BC-BoeingStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0682 11-19 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Boeing Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tentative Settlement Reached to End Boeing Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to add background on union's divided leadership,
other detail, and to recast. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The strike caused...'.
ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. and Machinists union leaders reached
tentative agreement early Sunday on a contract to end a 47-day-old
strike affecting more than 57,000 workers in nine states.
   Federal mediator Doug Hammond said he recommended terms that
eventually were accepted by both sides in a 14-hour bargaining
session that ended about 3:30 a.m. PST.
   Union leaders were divided on the offer, but the majority said
they would recommend approval.
   A ratification vote by members of the International Association
of Machinists and Aerospace Workers was set for Monday night.
   Terms of the three-year contract proposal were withheld pending
the vote.
   At Hammond's request, negotiators from the company and the union
returned to the bargaining table Saturday, the third such attempt
to find agreement since the strike began Oct. 4.
   The walkout is the longest for Seattle-based Boeing since 1948.
   Chief Boeing negotiator Larry McKean said strikers could be back
on the job as early as Wednesday morning, adding that he was
``certainly elated to have a tentative agreement here.''
   Tom Baker, president of Machinists District Lodge 751 in
Seattle, which represents nearly four-fifths of the workers covered
by the union, and Justin Ostro, an international vice president who
coordinates aerospace industry negotiations for the union, took
opposite positions on the contract.
   Ostro said it failed to increase wage rates beyond what Boeing
had proposed since Oct. 2, two days before the strike began,
although it did boost production bonuses. But Baker called the
settlement ``a substantial improvement'' over previous Boeing
offers.
   Ostro said the recommendation to accept came on a 3-2 vote of
the union bargaining team, on which he does not vote. Both sides
will argue their cases before members cast their ballots on
ratification, he added.
   Baker said ratification was favored by negotiating team members
representing 55,000 of those covered by the union.
   Hammond said his decision to submit his own recommendation to
the two sides for settlement was ``an unusual and for me a rare
step'' that he has used only once before in his 15 years with the
Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service.
   Boeing's previous offer included wage increases of 4 percent the
first year, then 3 percent each of the other two years; annual
bonuses of 10 percent of gross pay the first year, then 4 percent
the other two years; a reduction in mandatory overtime; and
across-the-board increases in retirement benefits.
   The strike caused airlines, in the midst of industrywide and
highly competitive expansion, to have trouble getting planes they
have ordered. Boeing has delivered 22 planes since the strike
began, though it had hoped to deliver 94 in the last three months
of 1989.
   At least six of Boeing's major customers last week reported
delays in receiving new planes, and some said they had to alter
plans for expanding or inaugurating service.
   Boeing spokesman Paul Binder would not comment last week on the
delays. He said only that production work was being done by
supervisors and any machinists who have crossed picket lines.
   Boeing estimated 5.5 percent of Seattle-area machinists and 40
percent of those at its Wichita, Kan., plant have gone back to
work. Union estimates were much lower.
   Machinists represent more than 57,000 Boeing workers, including
about 43,000 in the Seattle area, 12,000 in Wichita, 1,700 in
Portland, Ore., and a few hundred at sites in a half-dozen other
states.
   Boeing's longest strike was 140 days in 1948 by machinists. A
1977 machinists' strike lasted 45 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
