<FIRST>r i AM-DemoralizedCommunist     11-19 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Demoralized Communist,0790</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Academic Welcomes Progressive Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mathias Rothe, a teacher, says he
is among progressive Communist academics who long called for the
reform forced on his discredited party by a popular revolt.
   But many non-Communists in this rundown southern industrial
city, the country's second-largest where some of the first massive
protests began in October, are skeptical the party is genuinely
willing to revamp the political system.
   Rothe, 42, a party member since 1965 who taught ``basic
Marxism-Leninism'' to music students at Leipzig Conservatory, says
that to him and his progressive colleagues, ``It's satisfying for
us that what we indicated should happen for years is now taking
place.''
   No musician, however great a virtuoso, could graduate without
the course that has now disappeared as a requirement since the
revolt prompted sweeping changes in every area of East German life.
Rothe now teaches general political economy.
   At the conservatory and in other Leipzig institutes, the
students have voted to disband the Communist youth movement, Free
German Youth, in favor of genuinely democratic student councils.
   New Forum, East Germany's largest opposition group, condemned by
the Communists just a month ago, ``is making the kind of demands
which should have come from us,'' Rothe said in an interview in his
office.
   ``And internally, they did come. But not from the party as a
whole.''
   During an hour-long conversation, a visibly nervous Rothe cited
several incidents when he spoke his mind only to find some comrades
supported him and people at the top did not.
   In other East European countries, such divided opinions within
the party became evident in the government-run media or in the
public speeches of various Communist leaders.
   In East Germany, home of Prussian order, ``a Stalinist
interpretation of party discipline'' kept differences behind closed
doors, Rothe said.
   The government's refusal for years to institute Soviet-style
reform ``was a disaster, a catastrophe,'' he said.
   Like many other Communists he has no thought of quitting the
party that has given him power and a creed, but he is bitter about
the past.
   ``I don't know if one should put Erich Honecker, a man who is
nearly 80, on trial, although his guilt is immeasurable,'' Rothe
said of the former party leader, who was ousted Oct. 18.
   ``But Guether Mittag belongs in court without question,'' he
said, referring to the former Politburo member who was responsible
for the economy.
   In the eyes of non-party members, any of the approximately 2
million Communists can be held to account for the woeful state of
the economy, the bureaucratic meddling and regimentation of every
aspect of daily life in the past.
   The new leadership under Egon Krenz, who replaced Honecker as
president and party chief, has promised reform, eased foreign
travel restrictions and punched holes in the Berlin Wall.
   But skeptical demonstrators chanting ``opportunist,
opportunist'' have prevented any Communist officials, however
reformist, from addressing the weekly pro-democracy demonstrations
in Leipzig, a city of 550,000.
   ``I turn around to a man who was booing behind me and try to
explain that there are also good people in the party,'' Rothe said.
``But the mood of the masses is against the party at the moment,
which makes it inevitable that the first reaction is a chorus of
whistles.''
   Rothe and other Communists see hope in the reforms and say they
are genuinely prepared to stand in free elections.
   Much of the population and even some Communists appear
unconvinced.
   According to Politburo member Guenther Schabowski, 66,000
comrades have handed in their party cards this year and
resignations continue.
   Kai Hannig, 23, a New Forum organizer at Leipzig brewery, says
workers are also quitting the official trade unions. As in the
institutes, factory branches of the Free German Youth are being
dissolved, while New Forum has built up groups in at least 25 city
factories in just four weeks.
   The Communist Party remains, of course, an immensely powerful
body with resources far beyond those of any group in East Germany.
   But, as Falk Hocquel, another New Forum activist, noted, ``None
of the minor party officials has a tape recorder or access to a
computer to organize at the grassroots level as we are beginning to
do.''
   Hocquel recently attended a conservatory discussion, sharing the
platform with Rothe and others.
   ``The devil lies in the details,'' he recalled of Rothe's
contribution. ``It all sounds fine in general, but when you get
down to precise questions like the Communist Party's claim to
power, there's no basic change.''
</TEXT>
