<DOCNO> AP891119-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-89 1137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MasterofDisaster Bjt   11-19 0858</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Master of Disaster, Bjt,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Secretary is `Mr. Fix-It' For Domestic Crises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Samuel Skinner, transportation secretary by
trade, is getting a reputation as the Bush administration's
``master of disaster,'' the Mr. Fix-It for domestic crises.
   When San Francisco was jolted by a major earthquake Oct. 17,
President Bush immediately assigned his transportation secretary to
coordinate federal relief efforts.
   It was not the first time Bush turned to his transportation
secretary in a time of crisis. Skinner is Bush's point man for
dealing with the environmental devastation from the Exxon Valdez
oil spill off the coast of Alaska and the continuing strike by
Eastern Airlines pilots. He was the first high federal official to
survey the damage from Hurricane Hugo.
   While there is a transportation thread in each of these issues,
Bush has expanded Skinner's role to areas covered by other Cabinet
secretaries or agency heads.
   Skinner was in San Francisco again last week, walking the
damaged Bay Bridge. Before that, he surveyed Charleston, S.C.,
checking damage from Hurricane Hugo. He also is planning another
trip to the Alaska oil spill site.
   ``Sam has more or less assumed the role of a domestic crisis
management team, without portfolio,'' said GOP consultant Peter
Teeley, equating Skinner's role with one he said Bush played on
foreign policy matters in the Reagan administration.
   ``He's the one person Bush continues to look to when these
things arise,'' Teeley said.
   Skinner's staff has nicknamed him the ``master of disaster,''
erecting a small mock shrine with plants, candles and his
photograph while he was on his first trip to California after the
Loma Prieta quake.
   The raspy-voiced former Chicago prosecutor and mass transit
administrator has a less lofty definition of his role in such
crises as the earthquake.
   ``I'm available to cut through any paperwork, bureaucracy and
red tape if necessary,'' he said in an interview.
   Skinner, a 51-year-old certified pilot, has not escaped
criticism in his role as secretary of a department with 102,000
employees and a nearly $25 billion budget to oversee airways,
waterways, highways, railroads, and pipelines.
   He first stepped into controversy when he announced the
administration's refusal to intervene in the strike against Eastern
Airlines. Labor unions accused him and Bush of playing into the
hands of Texas Air Corp. owner Frank Lorenzo, whom they accuse of
trying to bust the union and sell off the airline.
   Skinner forced alterations in the stock buyout of Northwest
Airlines, a move that analysts say was partly to blame for the
collapse of plans by United Airlines employees and management to
take over parent company UAL Inc.
   The collapse of the UAL deal, in turn, is widely blamed for
triggering the Oct. 13 sharp drop in the stock market.
   ``He probably has primary responsibility for failure of the UAL
deal,'' said transportation expert James Gattuso of the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative think tank.
   Skinner disclaimed any role in the stock market decline, saying
the United deal failed ``for one reason and one reason only _ it
was not sound financially.''
   The March 24 Exxon Valdez spill of 10 million gallons of crude
oil into Alaska's Prince William Sound put Skinner at odds with
some environmentalists who claim the company's cleanup has been
inadequate.
   Skinner said he is satisfied with Exxon's effort, which has cost
the company hundreds of millions of dollars.
   His department also has been the focus of controversy and court
tests over mandatory random drug testing of employees in
safety-related jobs. The new rules go into effect next month.
   Skinner also has announced he is considering expanding the rules
to check for alcohol abuse in air, sea and rail transportation
industries.
   ``I don't want to mislead that I'm some kind of prude,'' Skinner
said. ``I occasionally have a drink ... but alcoholism is a major
problem in this country.''
   In dealing with air terrorism, Skinner has expanded his role to
that of a diplomat, traveling to Canada and Europe for meetings
with other transport officials after the Dec. 21 bombing of Pan Am
Flight 103 over Scotland that killed 270 people.
   The Air Transport Association, representing airlines, said
Skinner moved too quickly in ordering them to pay for and install
anti-terrorist devices that might not do the job.
   But association president Robert J. Aaronson praises Skinner for
his openness.
   ``I don't think there's ever been a secretary who was more
available for a meeting with a senior person from the industry,''
he said.
   With all the issues Skinner has handled in 10 months, he puts
one as his highest priority: plans to set a national transportation
policy after a series of nationwide public meetings.
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., who ran Transportation in the Carter
administration, said this is not a new approach.
   ``Every transportation secretary has tried it, and it always
ends with the staff writing up huge volumes of material and you
always come out in the same place,'' Adams said.
   Skinner sees it differently.
   ``I don't think anybody has looked as strategically, as
encompassing and as intermodal as we have,'' he said. ``I think it
will make a difference.''
</TEXT>
