<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Zulus     11-19 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Zulus,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>King of the Zulu Says ANC Has Shunned Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The king of South Africa's Zulus
complained to a crowd of 70,000 Sunday that he should have been
invited to a welcoming rally for freed leaders of the outlawed
African National Congress.
   King Goodwill Zwelithini spoke at a special convention of his
people, held at a Durban sports stadium three weeks after a crowd
of similar size welcomed the ANC leaders at a mass rally outside
Johannesburg.
   Both King Goodwill and Mangosuthu Buthelezi, chief minister of
the Zulu homeland, have been at odds with the ANC over the years,
opposing the movement's use of guerrilla violence against the
white-controlled national government.
   King Goodwill suggested the ANC might seek to exclude moderate
Zulu leaders from a role in negotiations to end white-minority
domination. ``I make the great plea that we are allowed to play our
Zulu role in everything that is being done,'' the king said. ``Let
us now put black divisiveness aside.''
   Seven senior ANC leaders were freed from prison Oct. 15 and
honored two weeks later at a mass rally.
   King Goodwill complained that the ANC leaders expressed no
appreciation for Buthelezi's past appeals for the release of
political prisoners.
   ``And I as king of the Zulus ... received not one single message
about the welcoming rally,'' King Goodwill said.
   Members of Buthelezi's Inkatha movement have been engaged in a
bloody power struggle over the three years in Natal Province with
supporters of anti-apartheid groups aligned with the ANC. More than
2,000 people have been killed.
   An estimated 7 million of South Africa's 28 million blacks are
Zulus, although many do not share the political views of King
Goodwill or Buthelezi.
</TEXT>
