<FIRST>r i AM-NorthernIreland     11-19 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northern Ireland,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRA Says Its Bombs Killed 3 Soldiers, Injured Sergeant and Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Republican Army
claimed responsibility Sunday for bombs that killed three British
soldiers on patrol in Northern Ireland and injured an army sergeant
and his wife in England.
   As concerns grew about a possible pre-Christmas bombing campaign
on the British mainland, the IRA also said in a statement that it
planted the bomb defused Nov. 13 outside the London home of a
senior army general.
   Following the bombings Saturday, Home Secretary David Waddington
renewed his warning to members of the public to be extra ``vigilant
and alert.''
   George Churchill-Coleman, head of Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist
squad, urged public figures last week to take extra security
measures.
   In its statement to the news media, the IRA said:
   ``Clearly the IRA cannot be beaten. The British public, instead
of fruitlessly condemning the IRA, should be taking to the streets
and demanding the end of martial rule in Northern Ireland.''
   The IRA has targeted army installations in England and
continental Europe as well as Northern Ireland in its bloody
campaign to drive the British out of the predominantly Protestant
province and unite it with the Roman Catholic Republic of Ireland.
   The Ministry of Defense said staff Sgt. Andrew Mudd and his wife
were driving out of the married quarters at the British army
headquarters for eastern England in Colchester, 50 miles northeast
of London, when their car exploded Saturday. People reportedly
heard the bomb one mile away.
   Mudd, 33, was in serious condition after having both legs
amputated, said Mark Shackell, spokesman for Colchester General
Hospital. Mudd's wife, whose name was not released, suffered cuts
and bruises, he said.
   Deputy Chief Constable Peter Simpson of Essex Police said his
force was searching for men seen near the barracks shortly after
the explosion.
   The army identified the three paratroopers killed hours later in
a roadside blast near the border town of Newry, County Down, as
Lance Cpl. Stephen Wilson, 23; Pvt. Donald Macaulay, 20; and Pvt.
Matthew Marshall, 21.
   A fourth soldier who was in the armored Land-Rover hurled off
the road by the bomb was ``very seriously ill'' with multiple
injuries, an army spokesman said. The soldier's name was not
released.
   The Royal Ulster Constabulary said the bomb, hidden in a
roadside wall, was probably detonated by remote control. Bomb and
forensic experts using metal detectors and helicopters with
infrared equipment searched the area make sure there were no other
bombs.
   Men in a second Land-Rover following a short distance behind
escaped injury and were able to call for help.
   Scotland had said the bomb found last week outside the London
home of Lt. Gen. David Ramsbotham, commander of the British Field
Army and inspector general of the reserve army, bore all the
hallmarks of the IRA.
   Commander Churchill-Coleman said the bomb was placed under a
neighbor's parked car and when it fell off was spotted by someone
nearby. Police evacuated the area of fashionable Kensington while
the bomb was defused.
   The soldiers' deaths raised to 10 the number of regular army
soldiers killed in Northern Ireland this year.
   Since the province's sectarian fighting began in 1969, 266
police, 601 army personnel, and 1,902 civilians have been killed.
</TEXT>
