<FIRST>r w AM-Riegle-Lincoln     11-19 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riegle-Lincoln,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riegle Revises Account But Maintains Policy Of Silence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Step by step, Senate Banking Committee
Chairman Donald Riegle is acknowledging more and more involvement
in the controversy swirling around the nation's costliest savings
and loan failure.
   Riegle, a third-term Democrat from Michigan, refuses to answer
reporters' questions about his meeting with federal regulators who
were examining Lincoln Savings and Loan of Irvine, Calif.
   But he is among five senators who received large contributions
from Charles H. Keating Jr., chairman of Lincoln's holding company,
at a time Keating was pushing for more lenient regulation.
   The five senators met with regulators who were examining the
S&amp;L's shaky investments in April 1987, but all deny any attempt to
sway the results of the investigation.
   Keating, who is scheduled to testify before a House panel
Tuesday, has said he certainly meant to be buying influence when he
made campaign contributions to the five senators.
   Lincoln's collapse is expected to cost taxpayers between $1.5
billion and $2 billion.
   Riegle's most complete public disclosure was an Oct. 18 written
response to a Senate ethics committee query in which he wrote:
   ``At no time did I ever initiate any contact with the regulators
concerning Lincoln,'' he said. ``It is my belief that my actions
with respect to this matter were entirely proper at all times.''
   Riegle asserted his only involvement was attending an April 9,
1987, meeting with the four other senators and the regulators.
   But in response to testimony before the House Banking Committee,
Riegle and his staff have added several details:
   _Although Riegle says he doesn't remember it, aide David Krawitz
says office records show the senator met Feb. 26, 1987, with Jack
D. Atchison, Lincoln's outside auditor.
   _Riegle acknowledges discussing the Lincoln situation March 6,
1987, with Edwin Gray, then chairman of the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board. In congressional testimony, Gray said those talks led to the
two meetings in April 1987 between senators and federal regulators
that are a focal point of the controversy.
   _And last week Riegle's staff confirmed a report first published
in the trade publication American Banker that in March 1987 he took
a helicopter tour of the Arizona real estate holdings of Lincoln's
parent company, American Continental Corp., including a lavish
resort.
   Gray met April 2, 1987, with Sens. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz;
John McCain, R-Ariz.; Alan Cranston, D-Calif., and John Glenn,
D-Ohio. Riegle didn't attend, but he joined the other senators at
an April 9 meeting with bank board examiners to discuss Lincoln.
   Some witnesses at House Banking Committee hearings have partly
blamed Riegle and the other four senators for delaying the federal
takeover of Lincoln until this past April and thus making it more
costly.
   ``Riegle decided to expend his political capital and time on
behalf of the savings and loan perpetrators instead of encouraging
the formation of victims' groups to get their money back and
helping to reform the system,'' consumer advocate Ralph Nader said.
   Riegle last was re-elected in 1988. He received $76,100 in
campaign contributions from Keating and his associates.
   Most of the donations were given at a March 23, 1987,
fund-raiser at the Pontchartrain Hotel in downtown Detroit, which
Keating had purchased and renovated. Riegle returned the money a
year later.
   Whatever the outcome of probes by the ethics panel and the House
Banking Committee, the political jeopardy for Riegle is obvious.
   Former Rep. Jim Dunn, defeated by Riegle in a 1988 landslide,
raised the issue of the Lincoln S&amp;L during the campaign, although
it did him little apparent good.
   Riegle's term doesn't expire until 1994, and Republicans have
said little about the controversy this year. But Michigan GOP
Chairman Spencer Abraham said Friday that Riegle should step aside
as Banking Committee chairman until the probe is finished.
   ``If he does not make a full disclosure to the people of this
state, I think I would want to re-examine whether he is fit to
serve as our senator,'' Abraham said.
</TEXT>
