<FIRST>r i AM-Cheney     11-19 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheney,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Defense Secretary to Visit Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Richard
Cheney will visit the Netherlands next week, making him the first
U.S. official to meet this nation's new center-left government, the
Defense Ministry said Sunday.
   No agenda items have been disclosed for Cheney's two-day trip,
which begins Sunday, and it is not related to the Dec. 2-3
superpower summit off the Malta coast, according to a ministry
spokesman.
   Cheney was invited earlier this year by Frits Bolkesteijn,
defense minister in Premier Ruud Lubbers' center-right government,
said the spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity in line
with ministry policy.
   Bolkesteijn is a member of the right-wing Liberal party, a
staunchly pro-NATO group that is now in the opposition.
   Cheney will now meet Bolkesteijn's successor, Relus ter Beek, a
Labor Party member known for his pro-disarmament views and
commitment to slashing defense spending.
   The new Dutch government, the third headed by Lubbers, has
announced it will cut the growth in defense spending to about .6
percent of the Netherlands' net national income and aim for zero
growth after two years.
   The new government took office last week, following a national
election Sept. 6.
   In the early 1980s, the Labor Party was strongly opposed to
plans to put 48 nuclear-tipped U.S. cruise missiles on Dutch soil.
That stance effectively banished Ter Beek's group to the opposition
benches for the better part of the decade.
   Lubbers decided to accept the missiles in 1985, but they were
never brought in because of the superpower pact on
intermediate-range nuclear forces.
</TEXT>
