<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0704 11-19 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0704,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoy Presents Credentials to Mouawad, Bush Declares Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with pro-Aoun rally, moves up background;
Picks up 5th graf, `Bush, in ...'; SUBS grafs 15-18, `The U.S. Embassy
...' with 2 grafs to delete redundant material, add background.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ODEY DAHER</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EHDEN, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Ambassador John McCarthy presented
his credentials and pledged the United States' support for new
President Rene Mouawad amid joyous parades Sunday in Syrian-policed
northern Lebanon.
   The latest U.S. pledge was contained in a message from President
Bush, which McCarthy handed to Mouawad along with his letter of
credence.
   The message also stressed support for an Arab League-brokered
peace pact approved by Parliament at a special session held last
month in Taif, Saudi Arabia, over the objections of Christian
leader Gen. Michel Aoun.
   McCarthy, who withdrew in September after reported threats from
Aoun, became the first foreign diplomat to present his credentials
to Mouawad since Parliament elected the Catholic lawmaker as
president Nov. 5.
   It also was the first time in Lebanon's modern history that a
foreign ambassador presented his credentials outside the
traditional seat of the head of state in Baabda east of Beirut.
Aoun occupies the presidential palace.
   About 5,000 Aoun loyalists staged what they called a ``freedom
rally'' in Christian east Beirut. They brandished Lebanese flags
and Aoun's pictures, chanting ``with blood, with souls, we support
the general'' during the hour-long display televised on Aoun's
television station.
   Bush, in the letter, assured Mouawad of ``the steadfast support
of the United States for your presidency and for Lebanon.''
   ``We intend to work hard in the days and weeks ahead to manifest
our support,'' Bush said. The text of the letter was made available
to reporters by the Mouawad's press office.
   ``I hope your election as president will finally bring an end to
the senseless violence that Lebanon has had to endure for far too
long.
   ``We believe that the implemenation of the Taif agreement will
be the first step toward the restoration of the unity, independence
and sovereignty of Lebanon over all its territory, free from all
foreign occupation,'' Bush added.
   Some 50,000 drum-beating supporters of Mouawad, a Maronite
Catholic, marched through the streets of Ehden in the foothills of
the Cedar Mountains as McCarthy presented his credentials at
Mouawad's ancestral palace.
   Dozens of ululating women tossed red and yellow roses at
McCarthy's bulletproof white Cadillac when it pulled to a stop at
the palace at 11 a.m.
   As the ambassador and his first secretary David Sutterfield
climbed out of the limousine, the women sprayed them with rose
water and rice in the traditional expression of welcome.
   Mouawad, 64, was flanked by senior Christian and Moslem
politicians during the ceremony. A band of honor played the
national anthems of the two countries in the courtyard.
   McCarthy said Mouawad's election ``is the end of the storm from
our point of view. ... The ship is nearly back in port.''
   McCarthy left for Damascus, Syria, after the ceremony and a
lunch with Mouawad to catch a flight back to the United States.
   The U.S. Embassy is in the east Beirut suburb of Aukar, which is
controlled by Aoun's troops. McCarthy and other U.S. diplomats
evacuated the embassy on Sept. 6 after Aoun loyalists besieged it
and left Lebanon.
   Aoun, who heads an interim Cabinet that he considers the sole
legitimate authorities in Lebanon, rejected as unconstitutional
Mouawad's election. He called the president ``a Syrian lackey
elected under the bayonets of Syrian occupation.'' He rejected the
Taif accord because it failed to set a timetable for a withdrawal
of the 40,000 Syrian troops who control 70 percent of Lebanon. Aoun
is backed by 20,000 mainly Christian troops.
</TEXT>
