<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Europe     11-19 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Europe,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Cheney-Defense</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cut U.S. Forces in Europe, Say Former National Security Advisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should cut its forces in
Europe and the Western military alliance must adapt to reforms in
the Soviet Bloc, two former White House national security advisers
said Sunday.
   ``The pattern of postwar politics as it has developed for the
last 40 years is now at an end,'' Henry Kissinger, the former
national security adviser and secretary of state from the Nixon and
Ford administrations, said in a televised interview.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney also said that up to 40,000 U.S.
troops could be withdrawn from Europe through ongoing East-West
negotiations and that the Pentagon budget could be cut because of
the declining Soviet threat.
   And Zbigniew Brzezinski, President Carter's security adviser,
urged that billions of dollars be shifted from defense to help the
nations of Eastern Europe move from communism to democracy and a
market economy.
   The ideas and proposals came as East Europeans, inspired by the
policies of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, instituted their
own reforms that have kept the West scrambling to keep pace.
   Kissinger, Cheney and Brzezinski, in separate television
interviews, agreed the Soviet military threat was subsiding.
Kissinger predicted that East and West Germany would be reunited
within five years, and said a unified Germany should be integrated
into existing Western security and economic arrangements.
   ``In the immediate future, I think that the use of military
force in Soviet foreign policy is sharply reduced, although I think
it is much too early to draw a final balance sheet since the
process hasn't worked itself out yet in the Soviet Union, and not
even in Eastern Europe,'' said Kissinger.
   ``I agree that NATO has to be recast. The present American
military establishment in Europe cannot be and should not be
maintained. But one has to make that part of a general European
security system,'' said Kissinger, appearing on the ABC-TV program,
``This Week with David Brinkley.''
   Cheney, appearing later on the same program, said, ``It's clear
that the likelihood of all-out conflict between the US and the
Soviet Union, between NATO and the Warsaw Pact, is probably lower
now than it's been at just about any time since the end of World
War II.''
   While administration officials have said they see no need to
change the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, Cheney said he hoped
that NATO and Warsaw Pact negotiations would finish work within a
year on President Bush's proposal to cut U.S. forces in Europe by
40,000.
   The conventional force negotiations would require both
superpowers to reduce their military presence in Central Europe,
with much sharper cuts in troops and tanks by the Soviet Union.
   Brzezinski, who recently returned from Moscow, proposed a
Central European recovery fund along the lines of the Marshall Plan
that promoted West European economic recovery after World War II.
   ``We spend about $150 billion on the defense of Europe, about
half of our defense budget,'' Brzezinski said on the NBC-TV
program, ``Meet the Press.''
   ``If we can reduce the level of the confrontation in Central
Europe, we will gain flexibility in dealing with Central Europe
economically, financially, that we haven't had until now,'' he said.
   Congress has authorized $938 million to bolster reform
governments in Poland and Hungary over the next three years, about
twice the level proposed by the Bush administration. However,
legislation to actually appropriate that and other foreign aid
money is bogged down over other matters, including whether to
withhold money from United Nations family planning programs that
might encourage abortion.
   Brzezinski said money saved on defense and used ``for the
creation of a Central European recovery fund ... would give the
United States the point of departure for restructuring existing
arrangements in Central Europe ... together with the West Europeans
and the Japanese.''
   On Germany unification, said Kissinger, ``I do not believe that
it is desirable for the West to let itself be maneuvered into the
position where we collude with the Soviet Union in keeping Germany
divided. It would be highly dangerous if we got in the way of what
the people of Germany want.''
   The security of Europe has been shattered repeatedly over the
past century because of expanding German economic and military
might, he noted.
   Faced with rapid change, he said, the West must ``negotiate the
pace, negotiate security arrangements in Central Europe, and
hopefully see that Germany remains part of the European Community
and the Western security system. And that is a tall order.''
   ``One of the tasks of American diplomacy and Western diplomacy
is to convince the Soviets that a Germany integrated into the West
in some manner together with a security system in Europe is safer
for the Soviet Union, and I would argue especially for the Soviet
Union, than a Germany of 80 million especially as a loose cannon in
the center of Europe trying to play both sides against the
middle,'' he said.
</TEXT>
