<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     11-19 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrrillas Threaten Colombian Oil Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will not yield to leftist
rebel demands for a freeze in gasoline prices, the state petroleum
chief said in a report Sunday after guerrilla threats of attacks on
petroleum facilities.
   The National Liberation Army, known as ELN, said Saturday in a
message to a national petroleum forum that it will renew its
attacks on the industry if the government carries out a planned
gasoline price rise at the end of this month.
   Andres Restrepo Londono, president of the government petroleum
company Ecopetrol, indicated at the forum in Bogota that the
unspecified price rise would go through as planned.
   ``My answer (to the ELN) is based on principles. ... For the
government, any type of extortion is unacceptable,'' Restrepo
Londono was quoted as saying in the Sunday edition of El Tiempo,
the country's leading newspaper.
   The ELN's threat to renew its attacks came days after the
government announced record oil production of 440,000 barrels for
the month of October.
   Industry experts predict petroleum will become Colombia's
principal foreign exchange earner next year, surpassing coffee,
which has fallen dramatically in price since the August breakup of
an international coffee agreement.
   Last year, petroleum exports earned Colombia $937 million in
foreign exchange, according to Ecopetrol. Colombia earned $1.6
billion in foreign exchange from coffee sales the same year.
   Ecopetrol estimates petroleum earnings will drop to $900 million
this year because of ELN attacks, which have cost the industry $485
million since they began in 1986.
   The guerrilla group, inspired by the teachings of Fidel Castro
and led by a defrocked priest, has perpetrated 112 firebomb and
dynamite attacks on the country's main oil pipeline and other
Ecopetrol facilities. The pipeline runs between the eastern Cano
Limon oil field and the Atlantic coast.
   
   The leftist guerrilla group is using the attacks to try to
pressure the government into nationalizing the country's petroleum
industry.
</TEXT>
