<SECOND>AM-Mulroney,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cnadian Prime Minister Calls For Support Of Gorbachev Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney
on Sunday praised the reforms of Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev during a stop on his visit to the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet president is ``a genuine reformer ... and should be
supported,'' Mulroney told reporters after meeting with Sweden's
prime minister, Ingvar Carlsson. ``Clearly, this man has taken his
part of the world down a brand new path.''
   He referred to the changes toward a more open society that have
occurred in the Soviet Union and other East bloc countries since
Gorbachev launched his bid to restructure the Communist society in
1986.
   Mulroney, who begins a five-day visit to the Soviet Union on
Monday, is the highest ranking foreign statesman to meet with
Gorbachev since East Germany began knocking down sections of the
Berlin Wall on Nov. 10. He is also the first Canadian prime
minister to officially visit the Soviet Union since 1971.
   Mulroney was scheduled to have bilateral talks with Premier
Nikolai I. Ryzhkov on Monday and will meet Gorbachev on Tuesday. He
was expected to sign trade agreements and may conclude a
cooperation agreement for the Arctic region, encompassing science
and technology.
   Before leaving for Kiev, the capital of the Ukraine, on
Wednesday, Mulroney will attend the inauguration of the
Canada-U.S.S.R. Business Council. Officials say about 200 Canadian
businessmen were expected in Moscow the same time as Mulroney.
