<FIRST>u a AM-SFQuake-Helm Bjt   11-19 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Quake-Helm, Bjt,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quake Survivor Mourned as Northern California Returns to Normal</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buck Helm, the longshoreman rescued from a
flattened freeway 3{ days after the Oct. 17 earthquake, was mourned
Sunday as a gutsy symbol of endurance. His death raised the toll
from the quake to 67.
   Helm, 58, died of respiratory failure Saturday night at
Kaiser-Permanente Medical Center in Oakland, said hospital
spokesman Ron Treleven. No other details on his death were
available.
   ``Buck's passing pretty much took everyone by surprise because
he was improving,'' Gary Frischer, a spokesman for Helm's family,
said in a statement.
   Helm had been taken off a kidney dialysis machine, and doctors
had hoped to wean him from the respirator that had enabled him to
breathe.
   His death raised the toll from the collapse of the double-deck
Nimitz Freeway in Oakland to 42. Overall, the 7.1-magnitude quake
killed 67 people, injured more than 2,800, left more than 14,000
homeless and caused an estimated $7 billion in damage.
   ``To many, Buck had become a symbol of survival and hope,''
Frischer said. ``For the Helmses, the thousands of cards and
letters from all corners of the world gave Buck and the family
strength and encouragement, and for that they are forever
grateful.''
   Others were rescued from the 1\-mile collapsed section of
Interstate 880 shortly after the quake hit, but Helm was the only
person to be pulled alive from the rubble after rescue crews began
searching the wrecked road.
   Rescuers had given up hope of finding more survivors when an
engineer testing the structure's stability saw Helm wave from
inside his small car Oct. 21. A large beam that fell in front of
Helm's Chevrolet Sprint saved it from being flattened.
   The 220-pound, 5-foot-10 Helm suffered a fractured skull,
fractured neck, three broken ribs, nerve damage to his leg and
kidney problems caused by dehydration. He already had diabetes and
high blood pressure.
   Helm, a longshoreman's clerk who worked the docks in Oakland,
commuted 250 miles each weekend to visit his family in the small
town of Weaverville.
   His former wife, Lorrie Helm, and the couple's children were
frequently at his side during his hospitalization. She said he
acknowledged hearing his family read the cards and letters sent to
him by well wishers but couldn't speak because of the respirator.
   Helm's rescue had buoyed frustrated rescue workers, who had been
finding only corpses in the rubble of I-880.
   ``I'm sure this will hit a lot of people hard,'' Steve Whipple,
the state Department of Transportation worker who found Helm, said
after learning of his death.
   ``I was under the impression that he was going to make it,''
Whipple said by telephone from his home in Pittsburg. ``It was just
going to take a long while.
   ``I'm still glad we found him and gave him a better fighting
chance than he would have had otherwise,'' Whipple said. ``It
picked our spirits up and made all our work worth it.''
   The news also stunned residents of Weaverville, where signs
saying ``Good Luck Buck, We're With You'' remained in merchants'
windows.
   ``It's really depressing,'' said Trinity County Supervisor Dee
Potter. ``An awful lot of people have been praying for him.''
   ``We were talking about what to do when he comes home,'' Potter
said.
   Funeral arrangements were not immediately released.
   Helm's death came amid other signs of hope in the San Francisco
Bay area. Traffic flowed across the Oakland-San Francisco Bay
Bridge on Saturday, the first time motorists were able to cross the
span since the quake knocked out a 50-foot section.
   In the Santa Cruz area near the quake epicenter, a highway
linking the coastal city with Silicon Valley was reopened Sunday
after being closed for more than a month by earthquake-triggered
landslides.
</TEXT>
