<FIRST>r a AM-Abortion-Mich 1stLd-Writethru a0749 11-19 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion-Mich, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0749,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Michigan Abortion Bill, Key Vote is Veto Override</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Fixes paragraphing in 1st two grafs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA ZAGAROLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abortion foes expect to chalk up another
victory with a restrictive law in Michigan, but abortion rights
forces are banking on the Legislature's inability to override a
promised veto from Gov. James Blanchard.
   Both sides say there's no doubt a bill restricting abortions
will pass in the House next month as it did in the Senate in
October by a 29-8 vote.
   ``With such wide public support for a parental rights measure,
we fully expect our representatives to reflect the will of the
citizens of Michigan,'' said Barbara Listing, president of the
anti-abortion group, Michigan Right to Life, after the Senate
approval.
   But both sides also acknowledge that the Democrat-controlled
House can't muster enough votes to override a veto by the
Democratic governor, who has pledged to strike down any bill
restricting access to abortion.
   The bill pending in a House committee would require unmarried
girls under the age of 18 to get one parent's consent before
getting an abortion. As an alternative, they could also seek
permission from a probate judge who would have to determine if she
was mature enough to make the choice and if it was in her best
interests.
   A similar bill already has cleared the Republican-controlled
Senate, which has enough votes to override a veto. But a two-thirds
majority of the House's 109 members is also needed to override a
veto.
   The action in Michigan comes on the heels of the Pennsylvania
Legislature's decision to place tough restrictions on abortion.
Pennsylvania's bill, signed into law Friday, is the first since the
U.S. Supreme Court's ruling in July, upholding certain abortion
restrictions in Missouri.
   The Pennsylvania bill requires married women to notify husbands
about abortion plans; abortions after the 24th week of pregnancy
would be banned; and women would have to wait 24 hours after
learning of their pregnancy before getting an abortion.
   ``The anti-choice people are going to run around looking for as
many victories as they can without people realizing they are not
victories at all,'' said Rep. Maxine Berman, one of the pro-choice
leaders in the Michigan House.
   In Michigan, a vote in the House committee is scheduled for Dec.
4, and Speaker Lewis Dodak plans to hold a full House vote and send
the bill to the Senate before legislators go home for the holidays.
   Since the governor has two weeks to veto the measure, that
probably will push the veto override vote into early next year.
   The Legislature has overridden only one veto in the past 38
years, that coming in 1977 on an obscure administrative rules bill.
   Berman said the anti-abortion victory in Pennsylvania actually
might have helped the pro-choice side.
   ``Pennsylvania is known as one of the most Neanderthal states on
this issue,'' Berman said. ``This might hurt anti-choice forces
because it was so out of line, so reactionary and so punishing that
it opened up a lot of eyes on what these people are really up to.
   Margy Long, a spokeswoman for Planned Parenthood Affiliates of
Michigan, said victories by pro-choice candidates in Virginia and
New Jersey gubernatorial elections this month have sent a warning
signal to politicians elsewhere.
   ``It's going to be part of the election, you can just bet on
it,'' agreed Rep. Michael Griffin, a sponsor of the bill. ``It's
possible this may end up as a ballot issue.''
   A year ago, Michigan voters decided to ban state-funded
abortions for poor women, taking action via a referendum after two
decades of failures in the Legislature. Lawmakers tried 17 times to
end the funding, but Blanchard vetoed seven and his Republican
predecessor, Gov. William Milliken, struck down 10.
</TEXT>
