<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-19 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in the Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to 2 feet of snow fell on western New York state Sunday as
temperatures climbed to record highs in three Midwestern cities and
dropped to record lows in Ohio and West Virginia.
   Snow showers also fell over northwest Pennsylvania, eastern
Upper Michigan and northern Maine.
   In New York state, lake-effect storms left up to 2 feet of snow
in Lewis County, 21 inches in Highmarket, a foot in Boonville, 9
inches in Barnes Corners, 8 inches in Sinclairville and 6 inches in
Salamanca.
   Scattered rain fell on west central Texas and the upper Texas
coast, and from northwest Montana to Washington state.
   Strong winds blew over the Great Lakes. Gale warnings were posed
for lakes Erie, Huron and Ontario.
   Winds gusted to almost 70 mph in Livingston, Mont. A high-wind
warning was posted for the upper Yellowstone Valley of Montana.
   But in Goodland, Kan., the temperature was a balmy 74 degrees,
snapping the record for the date of 73 set in 1949. It was 71
degrees in Scottsbluff, Neb., where the old record of 70 had stood
since 1932. Sioux City, Iowa, tied its 1936 record of 68.
   By contrast, the mercury dipped to 17 degrees in Youngstown,
Ohio, 1 degree below the old record for the date set in 1966.
Low-temperatures records were also set in Parkersburg (19 degrees,
25 in 1959) and Beckley (19, 20 in 1980), W.Va.; and tied in
Elkins, W.Va (14 in 1936).
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EST ranged from 20
degrees in Caribou, Maine, to 87 degrees in Thermal, Calif.
   The low for the Lower 48 states was 2 degrees in Gunnison, Colo.
</TEXT>
