<FIRST>r a AM-TrailerFire     11-19 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trailer Fire,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline in Heater May Have Sparked Fire That Killed Nine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAXTON, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline may have been poured inadvertently
into a kerosene heater just before it exploded inside a mobile
home, killing a woman, her five children and their three young
cousins, a rescue official said Sunday.
   ``They're really not sure yet,'' said Randy McArthur, commander
of the Maxton Rescue Squad. He said investigators were currently
focusing on that as a possible cause.
   Killed in the 3:30 a.m. blaze Saturday were Lois Ann Hunt, 32,
and her five children: Alisha, 12, Melissa, 11, Larry, 5, Bobby
Ray, 3, and Nikki, 2. Three other children staying in Mrs. Hunt's
trailer located about four miles north of Maxton in rural Robeson
County also died: Crystal Lynn Locklear, 5; Glenford Locklear, 4;
and Daniel Locklear, 2.
   Their mother, JoAnn Locklear, 25, of Maxton, is Mrs. Hunt's
niece. She and her companion, Richard Eugene Tyndall, 22, of
Laurinburg escaped the fire with minor injuries.
   The 11 people were sleeping in the 60-foot-long, three-bedroom
mobile home when neighbors reported being awakened by an explosion,
and saw the trailer engulfed in intense flames within three minutes.
   ``It sounded like a shotgun going off,'' said Anthony Locklear,
38, who lives across the street and is not related to JoAnn
Locklear. ``By the time I got out of the house, it was just
blazing.''
   Mrs. Locklear and Tyndall broke a bedroom window and climbed
out. A frantic Locklear tried to reenter the mobile home, screaming
``Save my babies! Somebody save my babies!'' said the neighbor.
   ``All the children. The children. I just can't take it,'' said
Doc Locklear Jr., 44, Mrs. Hunt's brother. ``I'm just lost. I don't
know what to say.''
   At about 3 a.m., Mrs. Hunt told her oldest daughter, Alisha, to
``make sure the kerosene heater doesn't go out,'' Tyndall told
Anthony Locklear. The child apparently got out of bed to refill the
heater with kerosene.
   Investigators said Alisha mistakenly might have put gasoline in
the heater. Another possibility is that a spark from the unit
touched off a propane tank Hunt used for cooking, officials said.
   Hunt supported her five children by working as a cook at a
nearby Hardee's. She had been estranged from her husband, Robert,
for more than a year, Evelyn Porter, a neighbor and friend, told
The Charlotte Observer.
   ``She lived for her children, they were her pride and joy,''
said Brenda Bullard, Hunt's friend and neighbor. ``She worked hard
for those kids.''
   Another brother of Mrs. Hunt, Kermit Locklear, drove up to the
trailer Saturday afternoon. He climbed atop the metal carcass and
reached into the charred bedroom dresser. With trembling hands, he
began pulling out singed pieces of children's clothing.
   Fighting back tears, he continued the search.
   ``Here they are,'' he said.
   Locklear had found pictures of his sister's five children, taken
last Christmas. He began handing them to his children.
   ``Don't you lose these now, you hear?'' he told them. ``That's
all we have left.''
</TEXT>
