<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AfghanRebelAid     11-19 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan Rebel Aid,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper: U.S.-Saudi Arabia Will Fund CIA Covert Aid to Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Saudi Arabia have
agreed to provide $715 million to fund covert aid from the CIA to
rebels trying to topple Afghanistan's Soviet-backed regime, the Los
Angeles Times reported Sunday.
   The money will supply mujahedeen guerrillas battling the Kabul
government with military equipment and supplies during the next
three months, the newspaper said, citing unidentified sources.
   The assistance is intended to nearly match the Soviet Union's
aid to the government of Afghan President Najibullah, which U.S.
intelligence estimated at $250 million a month.
   The Bush administration has already received congressional
approval for $280 million in U.S. aid to the rebels through
February, and the sources said the rest of the funds will come from
Saudi Arabia.
   The aid is reportedly intended as a message to Moscow in advance
of the December summit in Malta. Administration sources have
indicated the civil war in Afghanistan and other regional conflicts
will have a high priority at Malta.
   The sources said that in addition to Soviet assistance to
Afghanistan, the Soviets and the Cubans have provided new aid to
Nicaragua's Sandinista government, both directly and indirectly.
The Sandinistas, in turn, have aided leftist rebels in El Salvador,
where civil war erupted again this month.
   ``Whatever is happening inside the Soviet Union or Eastern
Europe, they (the Soviets) are not lowering their profile in
regional conflicts,'' said a source described as close to the
issue. ``The administration feels it has to be in a position to
keep up the pressure.''
</TEXT>
