<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua     11-19 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Holds Campaign Rally with Foreign Observers Present</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANDAIME, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 3,000 people attended an
opposition campaign rally along with about two dozen foreign
observers who had been invited to help ensure the peace.
   It was the first anti-Sandinista demonstration in Nandaime, 40
miles southeast of Managua, since clashes with government
supporters in July 1988 left scores wounded and arrested.
   Last year's violence led to the expulsion of the U.S.
ambassador, who the Sandinistas accused of inciting violence to
destabilize the government.
   The 14-party National Opposition Union even asked diplomats to
attend Sunday's rally because it feared violence from
pro-Sandinista groups, one European diplomat told The Associated
Press.
   It was the largest number of foreign observers at an opposition
rally since the election campaign began three months ago. A U.N.
observer group had nine observers, the Organization of American
States sent seven and there were diplomats from the Swedish,
British, U.S. and French embassies along with representatives of
foreign non-partisan organizations.
   Some of the observers met Saturday with the Nandaime mayor. One
source, speaking with the condition of anonymity, said the U.N. and
OAS representatives persuaded the mayor to cancel ``cleaning
projects'' Sunday that would have blocked streets along the
opposition's march route.
   The Opposition Union's presidential candidate, Violeta Barrios
de Chamorro, told the crowd to ``have faith.''
   ``The entire world is paying attention to all that is happening
in Nicaragua,'' she said.
   Mrs. Chamorro, whose family owns the opposition newspaper La
Prensa, is challenging President Daniel Ortega of the Sandinista
National Liberation Front in the Feb. 25 elections.
   Opposition Union leaders accused Sandinistas of harassment
during the past week in Nandaime.
   They said their pro-Sandinista mobs stoned the houses of
opposition supporters, workers were threatened with being fired if
they went to the rally and truck and bus drivers were told their
licenses could be taken away if they didn't attend a meeting also
set for Sunday.
   At the July 10, 1988, rally in Nandaime by an anti-Sandinista
coalition, 40 opposition leaders were arrested following street
clashes. They served from three months to six months in prison.
   The following day U.S. Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other
American diplomats were expelled. The United States retaliated by
expelling the Nicaraguan ambassador in Washington and seven
Nicaraguan diplomats.
   Neither country has allowed the other to replace the diplomats.
</TEXT>
