<HEAD>Margeret Chase Smith Remains Fair in Chicago Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Margaret Chase Smith of Maine
remained in intensive care Sunday but was improving steadily, four
days after she was hospitalized for chest pains, hospital officials
said.
   Mrs. Smith, 91, was listed in fair condition at Resurrection
Hospital.
   Ruth Pease, a friend who was with Mrs. Smith at the hospital,
gave no indication when the former Republican legislator from
Skowhegan, Maine, might be released.
   Mrs. Smith fell ill Wednesday during a flight from Bangor,
Maine, to Chicago while on her way to a meeting Indianapolis, said
her attorney and spokesman, Merton G. Henry.
   Henry said Mrs. Smith appeared to be suffering indigestion, but
the hospital ran tests to determine whether she was suffering heart
problems.
   Mrs. Smith represented Maine in Congress from 1932 to 1948, when
she was elected to the Senate. She was a senator until 1972.
   She was the first woman to serve in both houses of Congress, and
the first woman to have her name placed in nomination for the
presidency by a major party.
