<FILEID>AP-NR-11-19-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ExxonValdez     11-19 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers To Begin Replacing Portions of Damaged Tanker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipyard workers have removed 1,600 tons of
steel from the ruptured Exxon Valdez and plan to install new plates
to the hull of the tanker responsible for the nation's worst oil
spill, officials said.
   ``I don't think anybody has ever seen any damage like this
before,'' said Mike Blouin, a worker at the National Steel and
Shipbuilding Co., where the Exxon Valdez has been undergoing
repairs for the past three months.
   The ship spewed more than 11 million gallons of crude oil into
Alaska's Prince William Sound when it ran aground March 24.
   In the past seven weeks, NASSCO workers stripped huge steel
plates from the bottom center section of the hull, creating a
650-foot tunnel in the 987-foot ship.
   Each of the 3-4-inch thick steel sheets are about 44 feet wide
and 16 feet long and weigh about 100 tons. Many were twisted and
contorted in the collision, and workers found at least three big
rocks embedded into ripped sections of the hull.
   Workers removed the damaged plates by cutting the steel sections
free, allowing them to drop onto flatbed transport trucks parked
under the ship.
   The repairs are being done as the tanker rests on blocks about
three feet above the dry dock floor.
   Workers will begin the tedious task of replacing the steel
plates on Tuesday, NASSCO officials said.
   After the center section has been repaired, workers will begin
removing and replacing another 900 tons of steel on the right side
of the ship's hull, said Dennis Krumweide, manager of NASSCO's
structural engineering department.
   Another 800 tons of steel from other parts of the ship also will
have to be removed and replaced, Krumweide added.
   About 300 NASSCO employees will be working on the $30 million
repair project and Krumweide said it would ``be a piece of cake''
rebuilding the Valdez by the beginning of July.
   NASSCO workers built the Valdez between 1985 and 1986. It weighs
30,000 tons and can hold 16 million gallons of oil.
   Critics of the crippled tanker have said that the oil spill
could have been prevented if it had a double hull, but NASSCO
officials said Exxon did not request a double hull in the original
design or repair orders.
   The Valdez was towed 2,500 miles from Alaska to San Diego for
repairs, arriving off the San Diego coast on July 10.
</TEXT>
