<FIRST>r i AM-Vietnam-Elections     11-19 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Elections,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Holds Local Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Vietnamese voted Sunday in
elections for village, district and provincial officials, Radio
Hanoi said. No opposition candidates were permitted.
   The official broadcast, monitored in Bangkok, said voter turnout
at one Hanoi polling station was 92.2 percent. No results were
announced.
   Nearly 34 million of Vietnam's more than 64 million people were
expected to take part in the balloting for about 383,000 seats on
municipal, district or provincial People's Councils, the radio said.
   Nearly 480,000 candidates are running.
   On the eve of the elections, the Vietnam News Agency said that
public criticism had led to a number of candidates being
disqualified from the elections.
   Although Vietnam has made some major attempts to reform and
liberalize its economy, Hanoi's leaders insist the Communist Party
must maintain its monopoly on political power.
   The electorate has been given more choice among candidates,
although no opposition parties are permitted.
</TEXT>
