<FIRST>u w AM-CongressRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0782 11-19 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0782,710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Tackles Budget, Health Bills in Sunday Rush to Adjournment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 11-12, Yet another, with Bush veto of foreign
aid bill; picks up 11th graf pvs, According to; ALSO: the House has adjourned
for evening, but the Senate is still in session and the schedule for rest
of evening uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress made little headway in whittling down
a pile of troublesome budget, health and other bills in a rare
Sunday session, as members aimed their sights at adjourning for the
year before Thanksgiving.
   Like school children with bad work habits, lawmakers saved some
of their most intractable problems for the end of this year's
session. Predictably, they ran into difficulties.
   House-Senate negotiators, who on Saturday announced an agreement
repealing Medicare benefits for elderly people with lengthy
illnesses, met again Sunday to consider retaining parts of the
program.
   The House voted 349-57 Sunday evening to completely eliminate
the so-called catastrophic care benefits _ including the unpopular
tax on the elderly that finances the program _ but the Senate
rejected a total repeal on a voice vote.
   A separate deficit-reduction bill _ also agreed to Saturday by
bargainers from the two chambers _ ran into problems as well. Some
legislators complained it failed to achieve the $14 billion in
savings President Bush has demanded.
   ``It's not good enough to reach the $14 billion that everybody
says we ought to reach,'' complained Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
ranking Republican on the budget committee, emerging from a meeting
of GOP Senate leaders and White House officials.
   ``All of us recognize we have some concerns,'' said House Budget
Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., after a session attended
by top congressional Democrats.
   Confusion reigned about the effect the measure would have on
this year's federal shortfall, which congressional budget experts
think will reach about $141 billion.
   What appeared certain was that the measure would raise $5.3
billion in new tax revenues and include billions of dollars in
savings gimmicks, such as not counting the money-losing Postal
Service's budget.
   All parties seemed to agree extra savings would be earned by
keeping the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law's cuts in federal
programs _ which started Oct. 1 _ in effect until January or later.
   Yet another hot issue was dumped into Congress' lap Sunday when
Bush vetoed the $14.6 billion foreign aid bill, citing funds for a
United Nations agency that conservatives say supports forced
abortions in China.
   The House planned to consider a new version of the bill on
Monday. Efforts were expected to add language dealing with aid to
El Salvador, which is reeling from renewed fighting in its ongoing
civil war.
   According to congressional records, the session was only the
13th time the Senate has met on a Sunday. The first occurred March
3, 1861, when 20 votes were taken on the issue of slavery.
Incomplete records showed the House had met on four other Sundays
since 1978.
   There appeared to be few lawmakers in the Capitol as the House
and Senate were gaveled to business at 1 p.m. Some of those who
appeared in either chamber appeared frustrated that there was
little floor work to do.
   ``Where's the Senate?'' Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., asked a nearly
empty chamber. ``Where's the action?''
   In the first burst of substantive business, the House by voice
vote sent the $286 billion defense bill for the new fiscal year to
Bush for his signature. The measure cuts $1.1 billion from Bush's
$4.9 billion fiscal 1990 proposal for the Star Wars anti-missile
program, the first reduction in the program's funds in six years.
   But closed-door strategy sessions and bargaining among
congressional leaders dominated the day's beginning.
   Some of those talks involved legislation enacted last year, with
bipartisan support, extending Medicare coverage to victims of
long-term illnesses to cover their doctor and hospital bills. The
measure provided coverage to 33 million Americans.
   Many senior citizens have complained about the way the program
was paid for _ annual surtaxes reaching $800 this year for the 40
percent of the elderly who are the most well-off.
   The House voted earlier this year to repeal the entire program.
The Senate chose to leave reimbursement of hospital costs and other
minor provisions in place. After weeks of bargaining, Senate
negotiators accepted the House position early Saturday.
   The chief sponsor of the Senate version, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., threatened procedural delays to try to block enactment of
the repeal legislation.
</TEXT>
