<FIRST>u i AM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0715 11-19 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Filipino Voters Consider Autonomy For Provinces</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with returns indicating plan rejected,
winning approval in only three provinces. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most voters in 13 southern
provinces and nine cities rejected the government's plan for a
regional autonomous administration, officials reported Monday.
   They said the proposal was winning approval in only three
provinces.
   Sunday's election was to determine what areas wanted to join an
autonomous government proposed by President Corazon Aquino's
administration to satisfy Moslem demands for self-rule and end
their rebellion.
   Some politicians said the overwhelming rejection by a majority
of the voters would strengthen the position of Moslem rebel Moro
National Liberation Front, which opposed the plan. Southern
Christian leaders also had rejected the proposal.
   Critics said the outcome was a severe blow to Mrs. Aquino, who
promoted the autonomy plan but then declined to say if she was for
or against it.
   Radio and television stations reported that up to 90 percent of
the electorate in some districts voted against the plan.
   They said the election generally was peaceful.
   Ballot counting was delayed by a power failure in Zamboanga, the
election commission's regional center for compiling results. Final
tallies were not expected for several days.
   A commission official said the proposal was ahead in the
predominantly Moslem provinces of Tawi-Tawi, Sulu and Lanao del Sur.
   Political observers have said if autonomy us accepted only in
scattered Moslem areas the new administration would not be
economically viable.
   The region's 4 million Moslems form a majority in only five
provinces, which are geographically separated and are among the
nation's poorest. Christians form the majority in the provinces of
Mindanao and other southern islands.
   The Supreme Court ruled any province or city where a majority of
the voters approve the plan will join the autonomous government,
even if only one jusidiction approves. The court said the issue was
not whether to approve the concept of an autonomous govermnent but
only to decide whether to join one.
   The Congress approved the autonomy act in July.
   The Moslem rebel leader vowed to keep fighting regardless of the
outcome.
   Moslem insurgents raided 10 villages in Maguindanao province and
scattered violence was reported elsewhere Sunday but military
authorities declared the balloting more peaceful than most
observers had predicted.
   ``The voting has gone through and there was no major disturbance
that we experienced,'' said Maj. Hermogenes Esperon, spokesman of
the Southern Command.
   He reported clashes with Communist guerrillas in three different
places on Mindanao island, but said ``that is normal here'' and
unrelated to balloting.
   In Zamboanga, a largely Christian city 560 miles south of
Manila, troops guarded polling stations and armed foot patrols were
seen throughout the city.
   Mrs. Aquino forged a cease-fire with the Moslem rebels in 1986.
Peace talks collapsed in May 1987, but the cease-fire generally has
held. Before the Moslem rebellion peaked in the mid-1970s, about
50,000 people were killed and thousands more fled to the nearby
Malaysian state of Sabah.
</TEXT>
