<FIRST>r f AM-TransplantedBeer     11-19 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Transplanted Beer,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miller Uses its Muscle To Transplant Midwestern Beer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The name Leinenkugel might cause some beer
drinkers to raise their eyebrows more than their mugs, but Miller
Brewing Co. hopes the brand that has a loyal following in the
Midwest can do the same elsewhere.
   The Jacob Leinenkugel Brewing Co., a small, family-run brewery
for more than a century in Chippewa Falls, Wis., was bought in 1988
by Miller. Leinenkugel had developed a cult of customers in the
Upper Midwest, but now Miller is using its muscle to test the brand
on both coasts.
   The strategy by Miller, the nation's No. 2 brewer behind
Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc., comes amid a flat period in the overall
domestic beer market, as companies have grown more experimental in
trying to gain a bigger share.
   ``Miller really knows how to introduce new products,'' said
Robert Weinberg, a beer analyst and a professor of marketing
management at Washington University in St. Louis. ``If it works,
they jump on the bandwagon.''
   ``If the Leinenkugel brand tickles people, either because of the
name or the taste, Miller could take it national overnight,'' he
said.
   According to industry estimates, Leinenkugel sold nearly 100,000
barrels last year, compared with national brands that sell in the
millions.
   Miller, a division of Philip Morris Cos. Inc., started testing
the market for Leinenkugel earlier this year in Seattle and western
Massachusetts.
   Jake Leinenkugel, who remained an executive at the brewery after
the buyout, said Miller is trying to take a low-key approach in
promoting the beer.
   ``We want to go in a little mysterious, a little quiet,''
Leinenkugel said. ``We don't want to go in with a heavy media
campaign. We want it to be discovered.''
   The company is using this approach so the beer retains its
mystique, he said, and part of the promotion includes a description
of the beer's heritage in western Wisconsin.
   ``It does have that local, regional mystique to it,'' said Jeff
Mendel, assistant director of the Institute for Brewing Studies in
Boulder, Colo. ``I don't think they're trying to lift and
transplant it. I think they're trying to spread it.''
   Miller deliberately kept its name off the Leinenkugel label.
   ``I think there's a perception that a large mass producer
cheapens the product somewhat,'' Mendel said. ``It's possible
Miller's thinking they don't want that perception.''
   Said Leinenkugel: ``There was concern at the outset about the
company losing some of its identity after being bought by Miller.
We don't want to lose that, and neither do they.''
   Jerry Steinman, publisher of the industry newsletter Beer
Marketers Insights, said beer companies, including Miller, more
commonly have spent a lot of time and money starting a brand from
scratch. But in this case, Miller is taking a different approach.
   ``They have a base of something to work on,'' Steinman said.
``They know they have a brand with a reputation. Miller knows it
has the marketing power to take it to a new level.''
   Massachusetts, in particular, has been fertile ground for
regional brands, such as Samuel Adams and Harpoon, both based in
Boston.
   ``There's more and more local brands,'' Mendel said. ``It's
going to be a tough nut for Leinenkugel. They will have to rely on
their Upper Midwest roots because (in Massachusetts) there's
already a number of local brands.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891119-0074 </DOCNO>
