<FIRST>r f AmericanShipBuildingAwardedNavyContract     11-19 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>American Ship Building Awarded Navy Contract</SECOND>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Ship Building Co.'s Tampa Shipyards
division, which had feared layoffs because of lack of work, said it
has won a contract to finish construction on two U.S. Navy tankers.
   ``It's great news,'' George Steinbrenner, American Ship's
chairman, said of the contract.
   The Navy announced Friday it will pay $49 million for labor
alone in the two-year contract, which is expected to employ 800
workers, said Steinbrenner, who also is the principal owner of the
New York Yankees baseball team.
   The tankers were being built at the Pennsylvania Shipbuilding
Co. in Chester, Pa., but are now in the Philadelphia Naval
Shipyard, where the Navy moved them in late October after
Pennsylvania Shipbuilding said it couldn't complete the job for the
promised price of $331.4 million. The tankers are already 70
percent complete.
   Employment at Tampa Shipyards has hovered at about 600, but with
no major contracts in sight, union officials during the summer
warned of major layoffs and perhaps closing of the yard.
   For the quarter ended June 30, American Ship lost $2 million on
revenues of $13.8 million, compared with a loss in the same period
last year of $1.7 million on revenues of $20.7 million. For the
first nine months of the latest fiscal year, the company lost $6.6
million on revenues of $50.4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
