<FIRST>r f BC-AmdahlLayoffs     11-19 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Amdahl Layoffs,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Maker To Lay Off 400 Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amdahl Corp. cited expenses increasing
faster than sales in announcing the layoff of 400 workers at the
mainframe computer company's manufacturing plant.
   Company spokesman Bill Stewart said the layoff of 5 percent of
Amdahl's work force took place immediately upon its announcement
Friday, affecting jobs across the board.
   Amdahl makes mainframe computers compatible with those of
International Business Machines Corp., which this year cut prices
on its large machines by as much as 50 percent. Amdahl followed
suit, but profits suffered.
   For the quarter ended Sept. 29, Amdahl earned $32.9 million,
down 37 percent from the same quarter last year, despite a 15
percent revenue increase.
   Bob Djurdjevic, president of Annex Research in Phoenix, said
Amdahl remains essentially healthy and the layoffs _ Amdahl's first
since the early 1980s _ could mean a 2 to 3 percent increase in the
Sunnyvale-based company's pretax profits.
   John Girton, an analyst with Van Kasper &amp; Co. in San Francisco,
said mainframe computers are falling out of favor with some
corporations, which are turning to desktop systems. The trend could
hurt Amdahl and other mainframe computer makers, he said.
</TEXT>
